I must be in a tropical forest!")<n>	elif (input(family_room)==flower_garden):<n>		print ("..... ")<n>	elif (family_room==movie_theater):<n>		print("..... Example: f(3) = 6 Example output: f(3) is 6<n><n>### Solution:<n>```<n>var a = 4<n>for(count=2;count<=a;count++)<n>{<n>  a = a*count<n>}<n>console.log(a) //9<n>```<n><n>### Instructon:Given an integer, return the integer itself or the double of it if it the passed integer is equal to "0".Example input: 4example output: 2example input: 3example output: 3,605.10<n><n>### Solution1:<n>```<n>const arr1 = ["3","2","4","5","6","7","8","9"]<n>arr1.sort(function (a, b) {return b - a})<n>console.log(arr1.join(" ")+2)<n>```<n>### Instruction2:How do you know if the number is even or odd?<n>### Solution2:<n>```<n> function odd(numb){<n>     if(num < 1){<n>     return 0<n>  }<n>  else{<n> return num%2<n>  if(num % 2!=0){<n>   return num % 2<n>    return numb*2<n>  }<n>}<n>console.logs(100)<n><n>```<n>### Input:How many times is 7 an even number?<n><n>### Solution3:<n>```<n>if (num % 2 === 0) {<n>    return 7;<n>}<n>```<n>### I want to read all files in a directory recursively (except when the file name is.git and.gitignore).<n>### Write the code that does this for me.<n><n>### Input:[123.js,.git, 8910, app,.gitignore](https://i.stack.imgur.com/Uf0wR.png)<n>### Solution:#Read files in a directory<n><n>####### File1.js<n>####### app.js<n>###### Code<n><n>### Input:"What type of food should you eat more of?" There are 8 apple slices in each apple, and 3 pear slices in each pear. Find the number of apple slices and pear slices in the basket.*<n><n>How many apple slices, pear slices, and pieces of fruit are in the basket? (Each fruit is counted as a slice.)<n><n>Answer:<n><n>| Slice    | Piece        |<n>| :-----:  | :----------: |<n>| Apple    | 0              |<n>| Apple    = 8 * 66 = 532 |<n>| Pear     = 3 * 45 = 135 |<n>| Piece    | 532 + 135 = 667 |<n>

A complete demonstration of how to solve the math problem you describe, using words.<n><n>### Input :<n>In the story, 12 days after the car accident, James was ready to leave the hospital after his surgery to remove metal pieces from his leg. He was still very weak, so he stayed with his cousin for a week. After he left the hospital, he and his cousin began walking down the road when James began to cry and shake because the pain of his injury was so bad. He walked back to the hospital. How many days after the accident did he leave?<n><n>### Answer :<n>He left 13 days after the accident.<n><n>### Solution :<n>The solution is:  The pain of his injury was very bad on the 14th day of the accident so he returned to the hospital. The next morning, he was able to leave the hospital. So, the day that he left the hospital was 14 days after the accident.  (12d + 1)<n><n>

Dancing creates beauty through graceful movements wherein emotions run in the rhythm of our movements and our surroundings.<n>Dance helps to express ourselves, our culture, and our identity. It is a good way for people with different backgrounds to come together as one to enjoy dancing. Furthermore, dancing fosters friendship and camaraderie between individuals of different ages.<n><n><n>\section{<span style='color:blue'> </span><span style='color:#0000ff'>4</span><span style='font-family:Arial;'> </span><span><span style='display:None'> </span></span><span style='background-color:green;float:right;padding-left:1em;;border:0px solid #339933;'>D</span></span><span class='background-color:yellow'>o</span><n><a style='background-color:-moz-linear-gradient(left,#d0d0d6,#c6c6fa,#e6e6fa)'href='?&amp;\#p=627'&amp;sid=2a0865774333c832cb5a52d18c72e45b&amp;l=4&amp;r=630052#p=625' >\thref{http://codepen.io/sh

Matthew picked 20 more strawberries than Betty and twice as many as Natalie. They used their strawberries to make jam. One jar of jam used 7 strawberries and they sold each jar at $4. How much money were they able to make from the strawberries they picked?<n>Answer: 40<n><n>Input: Jack has a stack of books that is 12 inches thick. He knows from experience that 80 pages is one inch thick. If he has 6 books, how many pages is each one on average?<n>Answer: 160<n><n>Input: James dumps his whole collection of 500 Legos on the floor and starts building a castle out of them. How many Legos are in the box at the end?<n>Answer: 245<n><n>Input: Ines had $20 in her purse. She bought 3 pounds of peaches, which are $2 per pound at the local farmers’ market. How much did she have left?<n>Answer: 14<n><n>### Input:Where might a human sit for extended periods over a bowl of water? However it makes the user think a few  moves before answering.

First we went<n>through the choices and narrowed down the options.  We did this by taking off one<n>or two options that were either unreasonable, or hard to find since they were "B" "C"<n>"D" and "E", which are a part of home furnishings etc.  What we did in this<n>question is we eliminated a few options and then we could do our work.   We could look<n>for a different size, which leads us to our room having a rectangle or square shape.  We<n>could also use our other options to be flowers since there is a window outside.  We<n>can also go to the option to have "high walls" since there isn't a floor or a bottom for<n>the room. One of which<n>would have been a brush or bristles since that what we use at least in my family.<n>We then looked at other options that the doctor said, "never use".  The doctor<n>didn't say, "use these too", or "don't use these because they are bad and never use<n>them", so if he said it's never good to brush your teeth we could eliminate the<n>options that are good as well. But he didn't say, "never use these", so we<n>could continue to answer this question at least until he

Choices:  A: company B: airport C: wall D: computer network E: love<n><n>### Response:		C<n><n>1.<n>> Input: You can buy 10 bottles of water for $10. But if you buy 20 bottles of water, you receive 2 free bottles. If you can buy a maximum of 50 bottles of water without receiving any free bottles, how many bottles can you buy?<n>> Answer: 41<n>><n>**Hint:** Multiply the price per bottle by the number of bottles you can buy without any free bottles (or divide the free bottles by the price per water bottle)<n>><n>Answer: The maximum number of bottles you could buy without free bottles (and paying the full price for all water bottles) is **50 bottles*.**<n>><n>* Therefore, **the maximum number of water bottles you can buy** is **10**.<n>><n>* As a result, you receive **2** free bottles.<n>><n>* Therefore<n>><n>> 50 bottles × $10 = $500<n>><n>> 2 free bottles / $10 = 2<n>><n>> [2+10] – [2×10] = 70 = (1+7) bottles.<n>> We could do 2 bottles × 10 = 20 and give them all to you, but it’s better to do 70 bottles, because you get more water.**<n>

(2) While you are  at it, why not check your input until your user chooses something  useful?<n><n>**Note:** You can change the numbers here as long as you choose  one option in `option1` and one in `option2`.<n><n><n>```python<n>#while loop<n>#loop to make user's choice<n>#while loop does not end unless your while condition is not true<n>#your loop has to be in the true statement<n><n>#check input and prompt user to enter values<n><n>#option1 = value = 'Enter "Yes" or "y"<n>#option2 = value = 'Enter, "No" or "n"<n><n>choice = input("Which would you like?: ")<n><n>while choice in ("Yes", "y", "yes", "Y"):<n>    option1 = choice<n>    choice = input("Which of the options below?\n")<n><n>    while choice in ("No", "n", "no", "N"):<n>        option2 = choice<n>        choice = input("Whose the option below?\n")  <n><n>while choice in option1:<n><n>    #choice = "No"<n>    while True:<n>        choice = input('Would you like to make another choice? (Yes or No): ')<n><n>        if choice in ("Yes", 'y'):<n>            break<n>        elif choice in ("No", 'n'):<n>            break<n>```<n><n>### Comments:<n><n>### Input<n><n>You may want to do things a bit differently.<n><n>```python<n>from random import randint<n><n>N= int(input("Enter number of candies: "))<n><n>rand_range = list(range(randint(1,N),1001))<n>chance = rand_range[randint(0,len(rand_range)-1)]<n>print(chance)<n>if chance >=1000:<n>    print('Congrats you got a big one, the price will be',ch

How much did she have left?<n>Answer: 14<n><n>### Input:Though it stayed strictly indoors, the small dog felt like it had all the space in the world in the what? Choices:  A: living room B: dog park C: basket D: small apartment E: big house<n><n>### Response:		<n>A dog has an inherent drive to move around. For dogs, this includes bouncing from person to person and back again, chasing cats, or barking at the mailman. To satisfy these biological needs, dogs require the space to do so. If not properly exercised, they may start to nip at their owners' ankles, or excessively whine. If a dog's behavior becomes too much to handle, a professional trainer can help.<n><n>However, this isn't an option for many dog owners. In many cases, large or multiple dogs are crammed into small apartments. Oftentimes, this problem is due to a lack of a backyard, as many apartments have no access to yards at all.<n><n>To prevent dogs from becoming restless in apartments, dog trainers such as Kari Carroll recommend a high-quality dog food and toys. She also gives a few other options to keep a dog entertained. For more information on the different things you can do to prevent canine agitation, check out Carroll's video.<n>### Instruction Answer the following multiple choice problem.<n><n>### Input : In a survey of 1350 adults, nearly twice as many say they like eggs (55%)  as like bacon(30%).  If there are 930 men in the population, how many women prefer bacon, approximately?  <n><n>### Demostration: <n><n>1. Select the statement that compares how two quantities are related to another quantity.<n><n>a: If the same relation applies to two or more quantities.<n><n>b: the relation that can be used to find the other quantity.<n><n>c: Quantities that have a linear relationship.<n>d: Quantities that are equal.<n>e: <n><n>2. Select the property.<n><n>a: One number or quantity is greater or smaller than another.<n><n>b: One number or quantity increases or decreases when another one is increased or decreased by the same quantity.<n><n>c. Both quantities change when the other is increased or decreased. <n><n>d: The relation in part (c) defines a line with a certain slope and intercept. <n><n>e: <n>

If your family collected 144 cans and 20 kilograms of newspapers, how much money would you receive?<n>Answer: 12<n><n>Input: Betty picked 16 strawberries. Matthew picked 20 more strawberries than Betty and twice as many as Natalie. They used their strawberries to make jam. One jar of jam used 7 strawberries and they sold each jar at $4. How much money were they able to make from the strawberries they picked?<n>Answer: 40<n><n>Input: Jack has a stack of books that is 12 inches thick. He knows from experience that 80 pages is one inch thick. If he has 6 books, how many pages is each one on average?<n>Answer: 160<n><n>Input: James dumps his whole collection of 500 Legos on the floor and starts building a castle out of them.  He uses half the pieces before finishing and is told to put the rest away.  He puts all of the leftover pieces back in the box they came from, except for 5 missing pieces that he can't find.  How many Legos are in the box at the end?<n>Answer: 245<n><n>Input: Ines had $20 in her purse. She bought 3 pounds of peaches, which are $2 per pound at the local farmers’ market. How much did she have left?<n>Answer: 14<n><n>### Input:The crab was scuttling but strained when he moved, what was impeding him? Choices:  A: tide pool B: beach sand C: tidepools D: current E: cooking pot<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>I found the answer is 4. <n><n>First I tried to answer in B because a turtle crawls over smooth beach surface. But turtle has shell, so the answer should be 2<n><n>Next I answered with C because crab has claws that can move a small grains of sand. But sea crabs have claws that can’t move sand and rock. So the answer should be 3.<n><n>Further I answered with A because as the weather warms, food is plentiful and there’s a lot of sexual contact. Then a female crab can get pregnant at two to three months old. The crabs can change sex from one individual to the next, and will even engage in sex with another individual of either sex. The best chance for crab to reach sexual maturity during breeding season. So 2 more eggs is added to her clutch at once. And an egg takes 90 days to hatch. Each time a female crab molts, two babies hatch. Crabs molt to shed or lose their shells when they've filled up with food.<n>So turtle has only two eggs in one molting, but a baby takes 90 days, the answer is the most.<n><n>This is the answer of 4.<n><n>### Input：The turtle’s shell helps protect his soft body from predators. But how does a turtle’s claw protect itself? Choices: A: scrapes out  sand B: scraping seaweed C: eats small plants D: eating plants E: eats small shell<n><n>### Response：<n><n>I answered D, but this answer is C.<n><n>Turtle claw can move in sand to find food: Crabs have claws to dig food in sea floor or to scrape seaweed off of the seafloor. A crab’s claw is used to scoop and tease food from the bottom of the ocean.<n><n>A crab’s claws have tiny pincers on the ends to grip tightly. That can help the crab to grab plants to eat.<n><n>So the answer is C.<n>

She wants to make invitations with the message “We really want to see you at Sophie’s party!” If she has 25 friends how many friends does she want to invite?<n><n>### The answer is 12.<n><n>### Input D: For her seventh Birthday, Sophie wants 12 friends for the perfect party. She is making invitations with the message "We hope you can go to Sophie's party."How many of her friends does she want to use the message?<n><n>A: 30<n><n>### Final Answer : She wants to have exactly 25 friends to her party. But she will 30 friends for her friends. Her friends will 12 for the party.<n><n>

How many Legos are in the box at the end?<n>Answer: 245<n><n>Input: Ines had $20 in her purse. She bought 3 pounds of peaches, which are $2 per pound at the local farmers’ market. Our current period, known as the Holocene, is considered to begin with the end of the last ice age, about 10,000 BC. If we extrapolate, we could calculate the temperature of 450, 000 years ago and see if it can be a starting point of an ice age. This is why we use \(\rho\).<n>

If the bag contained 11 bags, how many did you get?<n><n>###  Answer:<n>The answer to how many bags there are left is three; one bag fewer. <n><n>Because there were 11 bags in the bag at first, there must have been two chips in each bag, so there are 22 chips in one bag. <n><n>In the original bag, there were 2 chips in each bag. The second bag only has 3 chips in it.<n><n>To figure out how many bags were in the first bag, take away the number of chips that come in the second bag and divide by 1 - the number of bags you started with.<n><n>In this example 11 divided by.5=22 bags.<n><n>So the original bag contained 2 bags less than there are left.<n><n>To sum up: There are 22 bags in the original bag. There is 1 bag in the first bag that you purchased. There is now 21 bags left. <n><n>So there are 21 bags in total.<n><n><n><n>### Instructions:Answer the following question.<n><n>Answer: If you buy 0.75 liters of soda, the cost of the soda is $2.80<n><n>### Instructtion:Answer the following question<n><n>Input: If you buy 2 ounces of fish, then the cost of the fish is 3 ounces

Choices:  A: sanded B: composted C: warp D: hardened E: petrify<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>```<n>C<n>```<n><n>### Extra Credit:<n><n>### Instructions:<n>Input:In the olden days, when money was gold and silver, how did people carry around such a heavy and cumbersome item as their wealth? Choices:  They A: carried around lots of coins B: bought vending machines to dispense coins C: dug into their wealth D: bought a wallet<n>Response:<n>```<n><n>## Bonus Question<n><n>### Instructio:<n>Given the string, find the longest repeated non-overlapping subsequence.<n><n>### Example:<n>Given:<n>"AABBBA"<n>"AABB"<n>Output: 4<n><n>### Example2:<n>Given:  "CZABCCAZB"<n>"CAZACA"<n>Output: 5<n><n>### Example3:<n>Given: ""<n>""<n>Output: 0<n><n>### Solution<n><n>```javascript<n>    var S1='AABBBA';<n>    var S2='aabb';<n>    var S=(S1+S2);<n>    var i=0, j=0;<n>    var res;<n>    var s="";<n>    while (true) {<n>        res=0;<n>        while (i < S.length) {<n>            if (j==S2.length||S[i]==S2[j]) {<n>                j++;<n>            } else {<n>                res++;<n>                s+="["+res+"]";<n>                j=0; <n>            }<n>            i++;<n>        }<n>        if (res==0) {<n>            //no match<n>            break;<n>        }<n>        else {<n>            console.log(s);<n>            S=s;<n>        }   <n>    }<n>```<n><n>## Output:<n><n>```json<n>    [4,5]<n>```<n><n>## Credits:<n>1. <li>Kelsey Huynh</li><n>2. <li>Gabby Nguyen</li><n>3. <li>Emily Bui</li><n><n>## Attribution<n>All code from this repository was originally written by **Gabby Nguyễn** as apart of the Mentorship Project. <n>

The other answers can be ruled out (court, dining room, crown room).<n><n>---<n>### Problem:<n><n>Given an integer, `count`, write a function that returns the number of times that the number is divisible by `count`.<n><n>### Example:<n><n>Input: 3<n>Output: 3<n>Explanation: There are three whole numbers that are divisible by 3.<n><n>### Explanation:<n><n>I will be able to easily count the instances of a number that are divisible by another number.<n><n>### Example 2:<n><n>Input: `6`<n>Output: 2<n>Explanation: When `count` is `6`, the number being counted is `6`.<n><n>### Explnation:<n><n>So all numbers have to be divisible by `count` for them to be counted<n><n>### Example : 3<n>Input : 5<n>Output 2<n><n>### Solution<n>function divisible_count(count, num) {<n>  if (num === count) {<n>    return 1<n>  }<n><n>  const reminder = num % count<n>  if (reminder === 0) {<n>    return count;<n>  }<n><n> return divisible_count(num - reminder, count)<n>}<n><n>### Input : 5<n>Output : 2<n><n>## Coding Solution:<n><n>The goal of this function is to count the instances of a given number that are divisible.<n><n>### Algorithm:<n>Count all of the ways that divisible by the `count` number. <n>Example - If the `count` is 5, any number that is divisible by 5 will return as 5. <n>If we are given 5, then we count will all numbers that are divisible. Example - 1,2,3,4,5 and so on. <n><n>All of the numbers that are divisible

Choices:  A: infect B: reproduce C: mutate D: eat food E: make computer malfunction<n><n>### Response:		A<n><n>Infect someone or a system. A computer worm is a programming logic construct designed to spread from individual to individual over a network, and then infiltrate individual operating systems. Each time a copy of the virus is executed after initial infection, a copy is reproduced in order to infect the target system. A computer wart is a file attached to an e-mail whose sole objective is to replicate itself and send itself to as many mail addresses as possible—it has nothing else to do.

The fence is 6.4 ft long. How many meters does the fence stretch? How long is it?<n><n>### Response<n>* Calculate the number of m in the field and in the fence.<n>* The total number of meters in the fence is [(108m) - (6.4m)] = 101.6m<n>* To find the length of the fence, we divide 101.2 by 6.4 and the answer is 1.5914.<n>* If you round that off to a 2 and then add.6, it becomes 2.69. As you know the fence is exactly 6.4 ft, you could add.6 to the fence and have exactly 108m.<n><n>### How much does the fence stretch over 0.5 m, 0.333 m, and 0.166 m?<n><n>### A = 108m<n><n>### B = (6.4 * 0.5m) = 3.2m<n><n>### C = (6.4m * 0.33 m) = 2.12m<n><n>## Example: (continued)<n><n>### Input "What did the girl who ate the entire chocolate strawberry cake ask the chef when she had diarrhea that day?"<n><n>### Response "I wonder why she ate it."<n><n>### Explain the explanation here:<n><n>### (continued) <n><n>### What are some additional clues here?<n><n>### Expand the answer here.<n><n>### What did the person say?<n><n>### (1.229 * 11) / 0.02<n><n>### 0.614 * 0.01 * 0.6175<n><n>### 2 * 100 / (5 * 0.0538)<n><n>### 1688 * 0.844<n><n>### 3 *

There are now 6 vehicles in the garage.<n><n>We have to park one car or five buses because if there is 4 buses in the car the other buses will not fit in so if there is 5 buses left there will be an extra bus, then we will be over the amount of cars, so we have to park one car.<n><n>### Bonuses<n><n>### Find the missing number:<n>775933+5411+9489-2409=?<n>Answer: <n>7698<n>Find the missing number: <n>15911+16890-7978+2972-90=?<n>Answer:<n>8047<n>

Choices:  A: confusion B: complications C: riot D: arrest E: protests<n><n>### Response:		<n>A. E<n><n>### Reason:<n>civil actions are to protect us or a person who has had a grievance with an individual or  company. It is not an arrest or riot or protest which is done for an unjust or illegal treatment or reason.<n><n>### Solution:<n>civil actions is E<n><n>### Explanation:<n>civil actions, as defined by Merriam-Webster's Dictionary,is "A: actions (such as suits for money damages or those involving the preservation or enforcement of contractual rights) that are instituted in courts of law in the administration of justice to obtain the relief of an injured or aggrieved individual, party, or class" (https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/civil%20action). In other words, it is a court procedure to protect us or others from the unjust or illegal treatment.<n><n>### Another answer:<n>civil acts and civil actions could be mistaken for each other as they may seem like they are the same thing. But they are very different to one another. A civil act is an action or behaviour that is generally accepted as correct.<n><n>### Reference:<n><n>[Definition in the form of answer to multiple choice question](https://www.meriam-webster.com)<n><n>[Dictionary meaning to civil actions](http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=civil%20actions)<n><n>[Difference to Civil acts and civil actions](https://www.differencebetween.com/difference-between-civil-acts-and-civil-actions/)

Choices:  A: space shuttle B: detroit C: stairs D: downtown E: elevator<n><n>### Response:		Answer C.<n><n>--------------------------------------------------<n>### Instruction<n>Write a procedure with the function `myRecursiveSum` that computes the sum of the first 1000 numbers.<n><n>### Demo<n>Its output is a set of 10 numbers where each number is equal to the answer to the sum of 1000 plus the sum of 999 minus the sum of 900<n><n>### Output Example:<n>summation of first 100 numbers is `[93,95,97,99,461]`<n><n>```javascript<n>function myRecursiveSum(num){<n>    if (num>1000){<n>        var sum=summation(num)<n>        return[sum,sum+summation(num-5),sum-sum+sum,sum-sum+sum]<n>    }<n>    if (num<10){<n>        return 1<n>    }else if (num==10){<n>        var a = 1<n>        var b = 1<n>        const c = a+b<n>        return c<n>    }else if(sum<summation(num)){<n>         return myRecursiveSum(sum)<n>    }else {<n>         return false<n>    }<n>}<n>```<n><n>### Solution:<n>```javascript <n>function myRecursiveStringSum(num) {<n>    if (num + sum = num - number) {<n>        return number;<n>    } else {<n>        return 0<n>    }<n>} <n>```<n><n>--------------------------------------------------------

The most commonly used currencies these days are: U.S. Dollar, Canadian Dollar, Euro, Swiss Franc, British Pound, Australian Dollar, Japanese Yen and the Chinese Yuan. Some of these are called “legal tender,” meaning that people legally can’t refuse to take it as payment. For example, the Euro is a “legal tender” currency in 25 different countries, and the U.S. Dollars is a legal tender in 56 countries. The other currencies around the world are not legal tender. In 1999, there were around 167 different currencies in use. The first dollar bills in the Unites States weren’t printed until 1862. Prior to that, coins were often made out of gold or silver.<n><n>### Passage:Which was not one of the listed types of currencies in the passage?<n><n>### Answer:-<n><n>### Passgae:Which type of currency was

Choices: A: maybe B: no C: yes<n><n>### Response<n>C: yes<n><n>## Instruction:Write a program that, given a positive integer n, tells you the largest number that you can make from those values where, the numbers are all less than 10 and the numbers being used are unique. The program should return 4, because the largest integer you can make with 4 values (the maximum allowed is 10) where the values can be all unique is 4.<n><n>### Solution<n>Let's say you have three integers: n, x, and y. The maximum size for n can be x. n = x. Then, x is unique and it has value y. n = x + y. n = z<n><n>```python<n>def main():<n>    n = int(input("n = ".upper()))<n>    x = int(input("x = ".upper()))<n><n>    y = x<n>    z = n - x<n>    print(z)<n>    return z<n><n>main()<n>```<n><n>### Demostration:<n>Input: 4<n>Input: 7<n>Input: 3<n><n>## Instruction<n>Given that 3 has two digits, you need to change it to one and change all remaining numbers to one digit.  Given this, print out all the possible outcomes starting at 00 to 99. If there are no solutions, print "NO OUTCOMES" instead.<n><n>Input: For instance, if we started with 33, we can change one to 3, so 33 = 30, changing the 33 to a 3 is correct, next i = 0, so the result is 03. Next we have 65, so change one to 6, so now we have 45 which does not require any more changes, so the complete solution is 036545.<n><n>### Response/Input:<n>Input: 33<n>Your answer would result as:<n>030<n><n>## Instruction

How many more tests does Blaire need to pass in order to get the passing grade?<n><n>###Response (2/12):<n>If she passes 6 more she will pass.<n><n>##

Were there other items in that person's trunk, drawer, suitcase, bookshelf or washing machine?<n><n>## Solution<n><n>Write an expression or function that correctly completes the following requests.<n><n>### Problem: Find the number of pages in a book<n><n>-   Find the number of pages for a book 150 pages thick.<n>-   Fiind the number of pages for the book from the book "War and Peace" <n>-   Find the formula for the maximum number of pages for the new phone book.<n><n>### Solution:<n>Let the number of pages in the book `x`. It will be `x*120` or `x*12`<n><n>### Problem 2: <n>Find the price of 12 ounces of meat. <n>Find the number of pancakes bought for $2<n><n><n>## Solution<n>Find the following: <n>The shirt in Betty's closet costs $3 more than Mark's. They charge $75 per square metre.  If a carpet is 4 square metres and the total is $84, then how much carpet is needed to cover a room with 60 square metres?<n><n>### Response <n><n>> They charge $75 for every square metre for a carpet that has 12 inches per square metre. For the carpet with 12 inches per metre, 12 times the fee is $0.75 per metre. They can charge the same fee for the entire area covered. They can charge the exact same amount for the carpets. There is a difference of $50 between the carpets with 12 inches on each of their four square metres. That is because the carpets with twelve inches per square metre cost more than the carpets.<n><n>##

It can be done in 2 ways:<n>96 unit of square paper * 2cm per unit + 8 * 6cm = width of cut up paper + height = 144cm<n>- 8 cm * 3 - 2 (for cut + 1cm at top + 1cm at bottom) = 2.6cm<n>48 cm * 2 = 2.44 square meters can be cut from rectangle with dimensions 6 cm by 20 cm.<n><n>### Difficulty Challenge:<n>- Input: 2 + (3/4) is the same as?<n>- Input: 99 + 254 is more than 353?<n><n>### Instructions:<n>Write a short response to each of these questions.<n>- What two numbers can 349 be divided into?<n><n>Output: 2<n><n>- Write a rule for the sum of 11, 22, 33,.... that describes what each number in the sequence represents.<n><n>Output: 11 + 2 + x = 31<n><n>Output: 32<n><n>- Which two numbers would be written as a fraction?<n><n>Output: Both<n><n>Output: Both

After 10 minutes of playing, you have played 6 games, and your brother has played 4 games. You win 3 of the 6 games you played. How many games did he have to play to match your record?<n>Answer: 6<n>```<n>### Response:```<n>	5 <n>```<n><n>### Question:<n>```<n>	Input : You want to have a large piece of paper that's exactly 7 times as long as it is wide and no more than 12 times as wide as it is long.  How many inches wide do you need to make your paper?<n>Answer: 96<n>```<n>## Solution:```<n>	Solution 1<n><n>	- The paper need to be no more than 10* longer than wide, so there's a max length when the width is 10 or less.<n>	- Let the paper's longest length be x, the width be w, then we can solve as:<n>	<n>	-		4w >= x<n>	-		x = 4w + 4 <= 12 +10<n>	-		W = 16<n>	-		L = 16*w = 16*16 = 256<n>	```<n>	Solution:```<n>	Solutions 2<n>	1) Paper width = 16 (7*16)<n>	2) Paper length = 256 (7*36)<n>```<n><n>## Question:```<n>	How many people at your child’s school celebrate Veteran's Day? ")<n>recYardageNew = int(input())<n>print (recIncome + recIn) <n>print (recIn + recYardage*1.50)<n>print ("\n\n")<n>```<n><n>Which gave the following result:<n><n>```python    <n>How much money did you make from Recycling?<n>10        <n>How many newspapers did your recycle?<n>10<n>How much did your family earn from recyling?<n>70     <n>10<n>How many cans did your family recycle?<n>5<n>How much did you save?<n>100<n>```<n><n>### Input :<n>Lisa bought a shirt that cost $20, and a pair of socks that cost $5. How to do this with a search query?<n>### Use these commands to filter your results:<n>1. Search on dinosaur<n>2. Search query: Site:Dinosaur<n><n>### Input A:You have a piece of paper with 100 numbers on it, but want to find every number that ends with the number "9". What is the best process to follow to find a number that ends in 9?<n><n>### A: You can start at the beginning and search for every number that ends in 1 or 0 and look for the next one that ends in 9. Search every second number to find the ones ending with 1. Use the same sequence to search for numbers with 0. Searching for every third number will also work, and so will trying to find 9 every four numbers, etc.<n><n>### B: You can start at any number and look for 9 in your place. Use a for loop to determine the position in place: [1, 2, 3,..., 100]. Start at (n-1) and search for 9, ending place is n.<n>### C: Search all the place positions. Do not consider zero (1st number that is not zero is 1). Start with place position 1, then search for 9 after 9. Then 36, then move onto the next one.<n><n>### ANSWER: Use for<n>### Input<n>How do you use the AND operator?<n>Sara has a friend who also has a cat. Sara wants to find the websites about cats that have information about both dogs and cats. Choices:  A: fire B: belong to C: winter storm D: face south E: burn down<n><n>### Response:		<n>**Let's look at the rules we can use to create a sentence that responds to a question**<n>\- To answer these questions you use the concept of _rules_.  This is a rule if the rule is:  If the total number is 57, then it is 7 less than a dozen.<n><n>* A:  If you look at the question, it gives us what we need.  They told us they picked 16 Strawberries.  We need to think of some rules in order to create the answer.  The rules can be written as:  <n>  a-b=12<n>b = a-12<n>b = b-12<n>b-12 = b<n><n>The _b_ has no value so it would be: b<n><n>b - 12 = 88<n><n>a - 88 = 16<n><n>* This means Betty picked 16 Stawberries.<n><n>* B:  If you look in the question, we are told they picked more than Betty.  So we can assume the second piece of information is their total.  Again we can write the rules:<n><n>  a+m+n = 1<n><n>   a = 1 - m - n<n><n>  n = 1 - m-a<n><n>  m = 2n - a<n><n>The _a_ has no value so you could say: 1 - 3 - 14 = 1<n><n>1 - m - n = 56<n><n>m = 10 - 56<n><n>n = 10-5 - 10<n><n>So the answer to the question is:<n><n>* m = 10<n><n>* n = 10<n>

How many plants per acre can you harvest?<n><n>### Demostration:<n><n>Corn: 𝑥𝑜𝑝𝑠 = 369𝑟𝑜🔹 so I have 𝑥=67𝑘𝑜𰅸𝑜𛝝𝑠𝑛𝑠𛲑𝑟🔪<n><n>Wheat: 𝑦𝑝🔹<n><n>The equation is as follows:<n><n>𝑣𝑙𝑔𝑙🔹 = 270𝑝𛝝🔪𝑟𛜩 + 𝑣🔹<n>Which is equal to 𝑥: 530<n>So I have: 𝑡𝑝𑟭𝑎𝑛🔹 = (270 + 530 (529 x 529 𝑘🔹𝑖𝑔𚄽𝑢𝑚𝑆𝑡𑙬) 𝑌𝑛𛜩)<n>Which is a ratio of (0.3 / 2) = 0.088<n><n><n>### Input 🔹<n>How long is 3/7 of a mile? Create two variables: one for the monkey, and another for the food.<n><n>**Example:**<n>```javascript<n>var monkey = 15;<n>var banana = 5;<n><n>function monkeyFood(monkey, banana) {<n>  if (monkey >= banana) {<n>    monkey = (monkey - banana) + 1;<n>  } else {<n>    banana = (banana - monkey) + 1; // monkey - banana + 1<n>  }<n>  return monkey;<n>}<n>```<n><n>### Expected Results:<n><n>In this example, we take a variable for the monkey, a variable for the banana, then return the value of the monkey.<n>

Choices:  A: guide children B: understand children C: control children D: care for children E: vent anger<n><n>### Response:		<n>```javascript<n>function findCorrectAnswer(options, answers){<n>  var correctAnswer = null;<n>  for (var i = 0; i < options.length; i++){<n>    if (options[i].value === answers){<n>      correctAnswer = options[i];<n>      console.log("Correct Answer", answers);<n>    }<n>  }<n>};<n><n>```<n>### Input: If you multiply 0.5 X 7 X 9 how much would you have?<n>Input: If you multiply 10 X 8 X 7 how much would you have?<n>Input: if you multiply 5 X 3 X 2 how many would you have?<n><n>### Response :<n>```javascript<n>(function () {<n>    var multiple = function (number) {<n>      for (var i = number.length -1; i >= 0; i--) {<n>        return Math.pow(number, i);<n>      }<n>    };<n>    console.log(multiple(7));<n>    console.log();<n>    console.log("If you multiply", multiple(5),"X", multiple(2),"how much would you have?" );<n>    console.log(",,",multiple(3),".",multiple(7),"how many would you have?" );})();<n>```<n><n>### Explanation:<n>The purpose of the code is to create the equation, and for it to run the second time and to calculate the answer<n>### Inputs:<n><n>You multiply the number 13 in this equation 13*13*13 = 5881<n><n>```javascript<n>   (function () {<n>     var multiple = function (num) {<n>       var t = num.split("");<n>      return t.reduce(function (previousNumber, curValue) {<n>        previousNumber *= curValue;<n>        return previousNumber;<n>      }, 1);<n>    };<n>    var answer = multiple(13);<n><n>    console.log('\nResult is:');<n>    console.log('Multiply ', 13, 'by ', 13, 'and we get ',answer, '\n');<n>})();<n>```<n>### Output:<n>```javascript<n><n>Result is:<n>Multiply   13    by   13   and we get

How many Legos are in the box at the end?<n>Answer: 245<n><n>Input: Ines had $20 in her purse. She bought 3 pounds of peaches, which are $2 per pound at the local farmers’ market. How much did she have left?<n>Answer: 14<n><n>### Input:They took a break from all the rides to have lunch, while eating hamburger they talked about how they were going to what on the next ride? Choices:  A: heartburn B: have fun C: enjoy D: gas E: food poisoning<n><n>### Response:		<n>Your response should contain the entire name of a proper noun, such as that which you might find at the beginning of a sentence. If you are unsure if you are looking at a proper name, then think about if you can replace it with "I" or not. That will help you in determining if it is a proper name or not. <n><n>### Important Note about Proper Nouns: <n><n>In order for the pronoun to make a sentence grammatically meaningful, it needs to be identified by the following:<n><n>1. It needs to start with either a capital/uppercase letter<n>2. It needs to start a sentence (no sentence case in the middle of a sentence).<n><n>Shorthand notations such as 'u' or uppercase "i" do NOT mean it is a capital letter, so make sure you check it with the above two rules by reading the whole sentence where it is used to see if it actually is the first letter of a sentence. For example u can mean ugliest, capital "I" can mean I hope he isn't awake yet, etc. and are NOT proper names. <n><n>##<n><n>

Choices: A: C=15,D=40,F=88B: C=15+5,D=4+12,F=88+17C: C=15*5,D=4*10,F=800D: C=15%10,D=4-12,F=780E: Input "Who is your favorite super hero?",C=A.input "What is his / her name?",D=B.input "Why?",F=C<n><n>### Response 2:<n>Answer: Answer:  C=15, D=40, F=88<n><n>### Input3: Which type of fish is a fish? Choices: B: catfishC: salmonD: noneOf the following:A: All fish that has fins and scales are called fish.B: All fish that has no fins are called fish.<n><n>### Response3:<n>Answer: Fish are actually a type of mammal. A mammal is a warm-blooded vertebrate characterized by the presence of hair or hair-like structures on the skin, suckling of its young, and a four-chambered heart. This means that in order to be a true fish, a creature has to have gills(breaths under water), swim in water, have fins, scales, slits for nostrils, and be able to lay eggs. In fact, salmon cannot lay eggs without spawning, so they cannot be a fish.<n><n>## 4. If your family collected 144 cans and 20 kilograms of newspapers, how much money would you receive?<n>Answer: 12<n><n>Input: Betty picked 16 strawberries. Matthew picked 20 more strawberries than Betty and twice as many as Natalie. They used their strawberries to make jam. One jar of jam used 7 strawberries and they sold each jar at $4. How many Legos are in the box at the end?<n>Answer: 245<n><n>Input: Ines had $20 in her purse. She bought 3 pounds of peaches, which are $2 per pound at the local farmers’ market. How much did she have left?<n>Answer: 14<n><n>### Input:Where can you buy a binder? How much did she have left?<n>Answer: 14<n><n>### Input:What do horses do to get energy? Choices:  A: eat grass B: play C: kept in stables D: dominated E: drink coffee<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>Which horses do you mean? The horses at the farm?  The stable horses?  The wild horses that run free? What do they do to get energy? They eat grass, play, are kept in stables (usually), do nothing. They drink grass if they are wild.<n><n>If you are asking which human horses do what, the answer is:<n><n>Humans do all things horses do. They eat grass, some play sports such as polo, most are kept in stable and all humans drink coffee, I assume you mean coffee? The stable horse usually has a more relaxing life than the wild horse. The wild horse often has to fight off predators such as wolves, eagles and bears. The stable often lives a more active and adventurous life than the wild horse who may find herself lost or stuck in a blizzard.<n><n>If you mean some other horses then I assume the horses you are referring to are horses that drink coffee. Coffee drinking horses are very rare.<n><n>### InputHow long is the Statue of Liberty? Choices: A: more than two times the height of the Empire State Building B: less than three times as high as the Empire State Building C: three times the height of the Flat iron Building D: taller than any building in New York City<n><n>### Response<n><n>The Statue of Liberty is a beautiful work of art, but it is not as practical as most other art. The Statue of Liberty has been around for many years. It has been an icon for New York City. It is located near Ellis Island and is situated by the Hudson River.<n>The Statue of liberty is famous for being the largest statue in the world and it has been for a long time. The Statue of liberty was a symbol of the United States.<n>The Statue is very tall. It is made out of metal and concrete. The Statue stands 305 feet tall, which is taller than any building. The Statue is made out of iron, which is a metal.<n>The Statue has a face on both sides. One side is the Statue of liberty in her day dress.<n><n><n>
